rm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma de Grainsby was born in 1124, in Grainsby, Lincolnshire, England as the daughter of End of line and End of line. She married Richard Wallace in 1142, in Riccarton, Midlothian, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 30 September 1206, in Well, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 82, and was buried in Well, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"1124–30 September 1206":"1124–30. september 1206","1124–1206":"1124–1206","1117–1180":"1117–1180","1143–1214":"1143–1214","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","30 September 1206":"30. september 1206","1206":"1206","1117":"1117","1214":"1214","1124":"1124","1143":"1143","1142":"1142","September 1206":"september 1206","1180":"1180","Riccarton, Midlothian, Scotland":"Riccarton, Midlothian, Scotland","Riccarton, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Riccarton, Ayrshire, Scotland","Grainsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Grainsby, Lincolnshire, England","Well, Lincolnshire, England":"Well, Lincolnshire, England","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1124–30 September 1206":"1124–30. syyskuuta 1206","1124–1206":"1124–1206","1117–1180":"1117–1180","1143–1214":"1143–1214","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":